@page "/gettingstarted/what"
@namespace BCSSViewer.Docs.Pages
@inject BcssService Bc

<MudContainer>
    <MudText Class="mb-4" Typo="Typo.h4">What is BCSS</MudText>
    <MudText>BCSS is runtime CSS generator for Blazor.</MudText>

    <MudStack>
        <MudText Class="@Bc["mt-16"]">
            BCSS has it's own user-friendly classnames (Called BCSS classnames like 'hidden', 'w-200', 'bg-yellow').
            In the background these classes successully transformed to valid CSS properties and styled your whole application.
        </MudText>

        <MudText Typo="Typo.h4">Why BCSS</MudText>
        <MudText>BCSS has several advantages:</MudText>

        <MudText>
            <b>Dynamic.</b> 
            All values completely transform on runtime. 
            It means users can easily change the CSS properties on runtime instantly.
        </MudText>

        <MudText>
            <b>Fast & Optimized.</b>
            BCSS has a great balance between performance and features.
            Optimizing the code is always a top priority.
            There are many performance enhancing features to avoid runtime overhead as much as possible.
        </MudText>

        <MudText>
            <b>Flexible.</b>
            There are other libraries that provides user-friendly classnames like tailwind.
            BCSS uses the Blazor logic and provides the widest flexible options.
            It is possible to write all CSS properties with BCSS syntax. No need to use any inline-styles or pre-defined CSS files.
            BCSS also has shorthand classname syntax to maximize
        </MudText>

        <MudText>
            <b>Rapid Development.</b>
            BCSS also has shorthand classname syntax to maximize the ease of usage.
            A good looking page can be crated in a single file within couple of minutes.
            Thousands of CSS code lines can be represent with dozens of BCSS classnames.
        </MudText>

        <MudText>
            <b>Lightweight & No Dependency.</b>
            BCSS has no external dependency. The total NuGet package has below of 100kb size.
        </MudText>

        <MudText>
            <b>Fast Learning Progress</b>
            There is no steep learning curve. For users are familiar with tailwind etc. libraries, takes less than 1 day to start development.
        </MudText>

        <MudText>
            <b>BCSS instead of JS and CSS.</b>
            Users no need to know JS. A basic-level CSS knowledge is sufficient to use BCSS.
            For users that don't have any experience with CSS, BCSS docs clearly describes the usage.
            All BCSS statements written in razor files with C# syntax. So even C# variables are valid for store and change CSS properties.
        </MudText>

        <MudText>
            <b>Use C# and razor files.</b>
            All CSS statements written in razor files with C# syntax. So even C# variables are valid for store and change CSS properties.
        </MudText>

        <MudText>
            <b>Complete .NET support.</b>
            BCSS supports all currently supporting .NET frameworks: .NET 6, .NET 7 and .NET 8.
            As a customized library of Blazor, can easily download with NuGet.
        </MudText>

        <MudText>
            <b>OpenSource.</b>
            BCSS will free forever and continued to implement better BCSS classname syntax and performance improvements.
        </MudText>
    </MudStack>
    


    <PageBottomRouting PreviousHref="/" PreviousText="Return Home" NextHref="/gettingstarted/howitworks" NextText="How It Works" />
</MudContainer>
